http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/%E2%80%98Work-on-medical-college-to-begin-after-March%E2%80%99/article14005921.ece

Chief Minister Siddaramaiah on Sunday said that the foundation stone for the district medical college would be laid after March.After launching various development projects in the city, he said that the government had approved 12 new medical colleges in the State. Earlier, only Mysuru, Ballari, Hubballi and Bengaluru had medical colleges.He also said that the government was giving more emphasis to irrigation, and had earmarked Rs. 33,000 crore for various projects. “In the coming budget, Rs. 60,000 crore will be allocated to this sector in order to implement pending and proposed projects,” he said.Mr. Siddaramaiah said that the government had brought in an Act to ensure that the funds earmarked for the welfare of Dalits and backward classes didn’t go waste.In his address, Water Resources Minister M.B. Patil said a bridge-cum-barrage worth Rs. 87 crore was being constructed at Herkal village of Bilagi taluk in the district. The project was expected to help fill eight tanks and irrigate 8,020 acres. Besides this, Rs. 24,000 crore had been spent on the Ramthal lift irrigation project.“This is going to be the country’s biggest drip irrigation project,” Mr. Patil claimed.Social Welfare Minister H. Anjaneya, who was also present, said the government had set aside 10 hostels for students from the Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes. They had been credited directly into the accounts of the students to prevent misuse.Earlier in the day, the Chief Minister also inaugurated the newly built Patrika Bhavan in Navanagar area. Congress MLAs and other elected representatives were present.